==English==
[[Image:Poster Buteo buteo.jpg|thumb|120px|Common buzzard, ''Buteo buteo'', an Old World buzzard]]
[[Image:Coragyps-atratus-001.jpg|thumb|120px|American black vulture, ''Coragyps atratus'']]

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|xno|en}} {{m|fro|buisart}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|buison}}, {{m|fro|buson}} (French {{m|fr|buse}}), possibly from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|buteōn||[[buteo]]}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈbʌzəɹd/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# Any of several [[Old World]] [[bird of prey|birds of prey]] of the genus ''Buteo'' with broad wings and a broad tail.
# In North America, a general term for scavenging birds such as the [[American black vulture]] (''[[Coragyps atratus]]''), and the [[turkey vulture]] (''[[Cathartes aura]]'').
# {{label|en|colloquial|derogatory|slang|often preceded by "old", the "old buzzard"}} A [[curmudgeonly]] or [[cantankerous]] man; an old person; a mean, greedy person.
# {{label|en|archaic}} A [[blockhead]]; a [[dunce]].
#* Goldsmith
#*: It is common, to a proverb, to call one who can not be taught, or who continues obstinately ignorant, '''a buzzard'''.

